WOMEN in vat en sit relationships can inherit and claim maintenance from their dead lovers’ estates. The Constitutional Court ruled on Friday, 31 December that sections of the Intestate Succession Act and Maintenance of Surviving Spouses Act was unconstitutional. Jane Bwanya from Zimbabwe approached the court for an order to uphold a Western Cape High Court ruling that the act should be amended to include, along with the word, spouse, the words, “or a partner in a permanent opposite-sex life partnership in which the partners had undertaken reciprocal duties of support and had been committed to marrying each other”. The judgment said the applicant argued the act treats surviving opposite-sex life partners differently to surviving same-sex life partners, affording same-sex partners greater rights than opposite-sex partners. Bwanya was the parter of multimillionaire Anthony Ruch, who died in 2016 without updating his will, which left his estate to his mother Lorna Ruch, who died in 2013. The court ruled: “Bwanya lodged two claims in terms of the Administration of Estates Act against the deceased’s estate. One claim, founded on the Intestate Succession Act, was for inheritance. The other, pegged on the Maintenance of Surviving Spouses Act, was for maintenance.” The court found the couple lived vat en sit “in a committed romantic relationship”.